Dr. '''Markus Jakobsson''' is a computer security researcher, entrepreneur and writer, whose work is focused on the issue of digital security.

==Career==

Currently serving as the Principal Scientist of Consumer Security at PayPal, Jakobsson has held positions as the Principal Scientist for [[Palo Alto Research Center]] and RSA Security, and served as Vice President of the International Financial Cryptography Association.<ref>{{cite web|last=Honan |first=Mat |url=http://www.wired.com/gadgetlab/2013/03/what-to-do-after-youve-been-hacked/ |title=What To Do After You've Been Hacked &#124; Gadget Lab |publisher=Wired.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bankinfosecurity.com/articles.php?art_id=183 |title=Interviews Markus Jakobsson |publisher=Bankinfosecurity.com |date=2007-01-29 |accessdate=2013-03-07}}</ref> Prior to these positions, he was a member of the Technical Staff at Bell Labs, and held a position at Xerox PARC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/cdnitmanagers/archive/2011/09/19/dr-markus-jakobsson-paypal-principal-scientist-consumer-security-past-principal-research-scientist-rsa-security-and-parc.aspx |title=Dr. Markus Jakobsson PayPal Principal Scientist Consumer Security, Past Principal Research Scientist RSA Security and PARC - Canadian IT Manager's Blog - Site Home - TechNet Blogs |publisher=Blogs.technet.com |date=2011-09-21 |accessdate=2013-03-04}}</ref> In addition, Jakobsson serves as an expert witness and is a member of the software and networking litigation group Harbor Labs.<ref name="harbor">{{cite web|url=http://harborlabs.com/people.html |title=Harbor |publisher=Harborlabs.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-04}}</ref> He has a background in higher education, having served as an Associate Professor at Indiana University where he was also a cybersecurity researcher and co-director of the Center for Applied Cybersecurity Research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/3759808.stm |title=Technology &#124; Users face new phishing threats |publisher=BBC News |date=2004-10-20 |accessdate=2013-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jon Brodkin |url=http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/print/9030058/Phishing_researcher_targets_the_unsuspecting |title=Phishing researcher 'targets' the unsuspecting |publisher=Computerworld.com |date=2007-08-10 |accessdate=2013-03-07}}</ref> He has also served as an Adjunct Associate Professor at New York University.<ref name="eweek">{{cite web|url=http://www.eweek.com/cp/bio/Markus-Jakobsson/ |title=eWeek - Author Biography - Markus Jakobsson - News & Reviews |publisher=eWeek.com |date=2008-04-30 |accessdate=2013-03-04}}</ref>

==Companies Founded and Advisory Positions==

In 2004, Jakobsson was one of the founders of the digital security company RavenWhite.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itworld.com/markus-jakobsson |title=Markus Jakobsson |publisher=ITworld |date= |accessdate=2013-03-07}}</ref> The Mountain View company offers digital solutions for businesses that pair customer identity with digital privacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkworld.com/community/node/8912 |title=Study: More phishing suckers out there than we thought |publisher=Networkworld.com |date=2006-10-18 |accessdate=2013-03-07}}</ref> In 2006, he launched securitycartoon.com with Dr. Sukamol Srikwan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.securitycartoon.com/about.php |title=SecurityCartoon.com |publisher=SecurityCartoon.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-07}}</ref> A website using comics to teach security awareness and understanding among the average internet user, it became the basis for the company Extricatus, LLC. Its aim is to decrease security vulnerabilities among companies caused by social engineering and human error.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phys.org/news99238473.html |title=Phishers can use social Web sites as bait to net victims |publisher=Phys.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-07}}</ref> With Extricatus, he unveiled the concept of Fastwords, an online password creation system where users create secure passwords made of a string of everyday words in order to make them easy to remember.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npr.org/2011/07/25/138672758/hunting-for-a-password-that-only-you-will-know |title=Hunting For A Password That Only You Will Know |publisher=NPR |date= |accessdate=2013-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Daniel Lyons |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/06/26/fastwords-the-new-online-password-security.html |title=Fastwords: The New Online Password Security - Newsweek and The Daily Beast |publisher=Thedailybeast.com |date=2011-06-26 |accessdate=2013-03-04}}</ref> In 2009, Jakobsson co-founded Fatskunk, a company that targets malware that attacks wireless devices such as tablets and smartphones.<ref>{{cite web|last=Naone |first=Erica |url=http://www.technologyreview.com/news/417905/hunting-mobile-threats-in-memory/ |title=Hunting Mobile Threats in Memory &#124; MIT Technology Review |publisher=Technologyreview.com |date=2010-03-05 |accessdate=2013-03-07}}</ref> He also serves on the advisory boards for Metaforic, a VC-backed company that markets software that other developers can incorporate into their own for greater security, and Lifelock, an identity protection company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metaforic.com/ |title=Software Immune System |publisher=Metaforic |date= |accessdate=2013-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lifelock.com/ |title=Identity Theft Protection - Avoid ID & Credit Fraud |publisher=LifeLock |date= |accessdate=2013-03-04}}</ref> In addition, he is a visiting research fellow of the Anti-Phishing Working Group (APWG), an organization focused on reducing cybercrime.<ref>{{cite web|author=SparkCMS by Baunfire.com |url=http://www.antiphishing.org/about-APWG/ |title=About APWG &#124; APWG |publisher=Antiphishing.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-04}}</ref>

==Education==

Dr. Jakobsson holds a [[PhD]] in computer science from the [[University of California at San Diego]], as well as [[master's degrees]] from both the University of California at San Diego and [[Lund University]] in Sweden.<ref name="bweek">{{cite web|author=Markus Jakobsson Ph.D. |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=134471584&ticker=LOCK&previousCapId=22854514&previousTitle=LIFELOCK%20INC |title=Markus Jakobsson: Executive Profile & Biography - Businessweek |publisher=Investing.businessweek.com |date=2012-08-28 |accessdate=2013-03-04}}</ref>

==Academic Research==

Dr. Jakobsson's early research publications were focused on [[cryptography]].<ref>{{cite web|author=M. Jakobsson, K. Sako, and R. Impagliazzo |title=Designated Verifier Proofs and Their Applications |journal=EUROCRYPT<U+2019>96: Proceedings of the 15th annual international conference on Theory and application of cryptographic techniques |publisher=Berlin, Heidelberg |year=1996 |pages=143<U+2013>154 |url=http://markus-jakobsson.com/papers/jakobsson-eurocrypt96.pdf |accessdate=2013-04-02}}</ref> Later research emphasis was aimed at understanding and preventing fraud.<ref>{{cite web|author=V. Griffith, M. Jakobsson |title=Messin <U+2018> with Texas: Deriving Mother<U+2019>s Maiden Names Using Public Records |journal=Applied Cryptography and Network Security |publisher=New York, NY |year=2005 |pages= |url=http://markus-jakobsson.com/papers/jakobsson-acns05-texas.pdf |accessdate=2013-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=M. Gandhi, M. Jakobsson, and J. Ratkiewicz |title=Badvertisements: Stealthy click-fraud with unwitting accessories |journal=Journal of Digital Forensics Practice |volume=1 |issue=2 |publisher= |year=2006 |pages= |url=http://markus-jakobsson.com/papers/jakobsson-jdfp06.pdf |accessdate=2013-04-02}}</ref><ref name="phishing">{{cite web|author=T. N. Jagatic, N. A. Johnson, M. Jakobsson, and F. Menczer |title=Social phishing |journal=Commun. ACM |volume=50 |issue=10 |publisher= |year=2007 |pages=94<U+2013>100 |url=http://markus-jakobsson.com/papers/jakobsson-commacm07.pdf |accessdate=2013-04-02}}</ref> With [[Filippo Menczer]] and two students, he also conducted live experiments on Internet users in order to determine the ways users were likely to fall victim to various forms on online fraud.<ref name="phishing" /><ref>{{cite web|author=T. N. Jagatic, N. A. Johnson, M. Jakobsson, and F. Menczer |title=Designing and Conducting Phishing Experiments |journal=In IEEE Technology and Society Magazine, Special Issue on Usability and Security |volume= |issue= |publisher= |year=2007 |pages= |url=http://markus-jakobsson.com/papers/jakobsson-ieeets07.pdf |accessdate=2013-04-02}}</ref> His later research was focused toward mobile security and the detection of malware on mobile platforms.<ref>{{cite web|author=M. Jakobsson and K. Johansson |title=Retroactive Detection of Malware With Applications to Mobile Platforms |journal=HotSec 2010 |volume= |issue= |publisher=Washington, DC |year=2010 |pages= |url=http://markus-jakobsson.com/papers/jakobsson-hotsec10.pdf |accessdate=2013-04-02}}</ref>

==Bibliography==

Dr. Jakobsson is the author or editor of a series of books and studies dealing with the world of internet security and its practical applications for businesses and individual users.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/Markus-Jakobsson/e/B006J03SOA |title=Markus Jakobsson: Books, Biography, Blog, Audiobooks, Kindle |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-04}}</ref>

* ''Phishing and Countermeasures: Understanding the Increasing Problem of Electronic Identity Theft'', Markus Jakobsson, Steven Myers - Editors, Wiley-Interscience, 2006
*  ''Crimeware: Understanding New Attacks and Defenses'', Markus Jakobsson, Zulfikar Ramzan - Authors, Addison-Wesley Professional, 2008
*  ''Towards Trustworthy Elections: New Directions in Electronic Voting (Lecture Notes in Computer Science / Security and Cryptology)'', David Chaum, Markus Jakobsson, Ronald L. Rivest, Peter Y. A. Ryan, Josh Benaloh, Miroslaw Kutylowski, Editors, Springer, 2010
*  ''The Death of the Internet'', Markus Jakobsson - Editor, Wiley-IEEE Computer Society Pr, 2012
*  ''Mobile Authentication: Problems and Solutions (SpringerBriefs in Computer Science)'', Markus Jakobsson, Author, Springer, 2012

